WEBVTT

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:32.640
Hello, everyone. Welcome once again to WordPress 
Accessibility Day 2020. My name is Ahmed Kabir

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:37.600
Chaion, and I'm working as a business development 
manager at weDevs. I'm also a regular contributor

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:43.600
to the making WordPress documentation, design, 
polyglots, accessibility, hosting, community,

00:00:43.600 --> 00:00:49.440
learn WordPress, and marketing. I will be your 
host for this session. You're here for the 8

00:00:49.440 --> 00:00:55.600
a.m UTC talk with Hidde de Vries. Please feel 
free to add your questions to the YouTube chat,

00:00:55.600 --> 00:01:01.440
and we'll answer those at the end. Your 
content management system plays a decisive

00:01:01.440 --> 00:01:09.360
part in creating accessible content suggest the 
Authoring Tools Accessibility Guideline - ATAG.

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:16.000
Whenever a content designer creates content the 
CMS could help with the accessibility of it.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:22.480
For instance, when a designer drops in an image, 
the CMS could point to the ideal text alternative

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:29.440
or calculate the consequences for color contrast. 
In this talk, you will learn more about what ATAG

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:36.160
is and how, with ATAG in mind, CMSs can 
personally assist content editors on their way

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:43.680
to a more accessible website. The speaker for this 
talk, Hidde, is a web developer and accessibility

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:50.480
specialist at the W3C's Web Accessibility 
Initiative, or WAI based in Rotterdam,

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:56.400
Netherlands. As part of the WAI guide project, 
he works on the accessibility of authoring tools

00:01:56.400 --> 00:02:02.800
like CMSs and website creators, and guidance 
that supports the Web Content Accessibility

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:08.720
Guidelines - WCAG. He has over 10 years 
of experience working as a freelance

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:14.160
front-end developer and accessibility person 
for organizations like Mozilla and the Dutch

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:21.120
government. On his blog he writes regularly about 
reusable components, CSS, and web accessibility.

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:36.840
Which brings to the session "Your CMS is an 
accessibility assistant." Take it away, Hidde.

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:47.280
[Hidde] Hello, this is Hidde, and I'm here today to 
talk about how your CMS could be seen as an

00:02:47.280 --> 00:02:52.160
accessibility assistant, and how that can help 
organizations, including maybe the clients, or the

00:02:52.160 --> 00:03:00.320
users of a CMS. Very briefly about myself, I work 
as an accessibility specialist at the W3C, the

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:07.520
World Wide Web consortium, where i worked at the 
Web Accessibility Initiative. We have a website

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:12.000
which I'd like to plug. On our website there is 
loads of information about web accessibility,

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:18.800
about planning, designing, developing, testing, 
advocating, and training for web accessibility.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:25.200
So many people don't know about all these 
amazing resources that are on this website, um,

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:32.080
so I thought I'd mention it. But disclaimer I, I 
do work on some of the content for this site. Now,

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:38.960
I focus mostly in my work on authoring tools. And 
authoring tools, if you're not familiar with that

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:46.000
phrase, they are tools that create web content. 
And with that, as probably won't surprise you,

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.760
they are also tools that can improve a lot of web 
accessibility at once. That is a very exciting

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:56.400
prospect, I think, and I'll be talking a lot 
today about how we can, can make that a reality.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:04:03.360
How can we really employ authoring tools to, to 
improve accessibility in, in many places at once.

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:09.200
Now, first let's look at a couple of examples 
of authoring tools. We're talking about things

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:14.800
like WYSIWYG editors, course creators, learning 
management systems, or anything that they use in

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:20.720
online education - very important in times of 
COVID - content management systems, of course,

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:28.880
wikipedia, your "save as html" functionality, 
social media, form generators, site builders.

00:04:28.880 --> 00:04:33.920
Lots of these, these different things, all have 
in common that they create content for the web,

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:39.040
or that they they provide some sort of interface 
for their users to create something that will

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:45.440
ultimately live on the web. Now specifically 
about CMSs - we're at WordPress Accessibility

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:52.640
Day - you can think of the authoring tool as the 
CMS itself. And I imagine some people watching

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:58.640
this today work, work on WordPress core, or have 
provided some patches for it, or maybe considering

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:03.360
contributing to WordPress, but others may 
be working on plugins like form builders,

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:09.600
custom field managing stuff, things where you can 
manage events, or social media, cookie banners,

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:14.640
even. Just anything that you can plug into a 
website, and that will also create web content,

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:19.040
it will also be considered as an authoring 
tool. When I talk about CMSs in this talk,

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:28.480
I very much also mean plugins and themes, as 
well. Now, the web is meant to work for everyone.

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:35.200
That is a point that we take very seriously at the 
W3C. This is a photograph of Sir Tim Berners-Lee,

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:41.040
the inventor of the web, who was at the 
opening ceremony of the London Olympics

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:48.000
in 2012. And he made these four words appear. 
"This is for everyone." Now I think and I haven't,

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:52.480
you know, I haven't checked this with him 
personally, but I think you could interpret

00:05:52.480 --> 00:06:01.360
this in various ways. One is that the web should 
be available for, for everyone to, to kind of

00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:06.960
get onto the web. So, of course you need to get a 
cable subscription, or go to a library, and maybe

00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:12.560
pay to use a computer. But, ultimately, the web 
is available for everyone - this is for everyone.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:19.600
Secondly, I think everyone can have a website 
on the web, as well. You don't need to apply for

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:24.640
permit at your local government, or something 
like that, or you know do, do something very

00:06:24.640 --> 00:06:30.400
special. You need to have a web server, or rent 
one, and you can put some HTML on there and make

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:35.760
it available on the URL. So, in that sense it's 
also for everyone. And, and the third way that

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:42.000
you could read this, "this is for everyone" is as, 
this is something that should work for everyone,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:48.000
including people with disabilities. And that 
is the definition that we use at, um, at WAI.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:54.080
Making the web work for people with disabilities 
is what web accessibility is about. We're,

00:06:54.080 --> 00:07:00.560
we want to make sure that this is for everyone. 
Now, to that extent at WAI, we have three web

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:06.640
standards that are about the accessibility of, of 
web content, ultimately. Now, many people will be

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:12.640
familiar with the WCAG standard, which stands 
for the web content accessibility guidelines,

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:18.480
but there's two more sets of guidelines, that are 
very closely related, and that together really

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:24.160
create that picture of an accessible web. So there 
is, uh, the web content accessibility guidelines

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:29.840
about web content itself, but what about the 
software that people use to access web content?

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:36.080
Browsers, or user agents. There's a specific 
center for that, the User Agent Accessibility

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:42.240
Guidelines - UAAG. And what about the software 
that creates that content, authoring tools? And

00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:46.960
for that we have the Authoring Tools Accessibility 
Guidelines. So together, these three standards,

00:07:46.960 --> 00:07:52.320
they all say something about the accessibility 
of web content. About the content itself,

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:58.400
about the software we use to view the content, and 
about the software we use to create the content.

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:04.400
Now authoring tools are very important, and 
CMS is with that. They're essential in this

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:09.760
picture of web accessibility. Because if we get 
it right, if we get it right in authoring tools,

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:14.160
we'll be able to include more content creators. 
We can have more people publish stuff on the web.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:19.920
And the second reason that I think authoring 
tools are so important and exciting,

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:24.800
is that content creators may be allowed 
to fix accessibility problems before their

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:29.360
website goes live. It is the central central 
theme of what I, what I want to say today.

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:38.240
Now the standard for authoring tools, as I said, 
is ATAG. With the latest iteration ATAG 2.0.

00:08:38.800 --> 00:08:42.640
Now, in ATAG, and I'll talk 
about a lot of ATAG today,

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:48.640
but if you want to read it at your own pace you 
can visit the source called "ATAG at a glance."

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:53.920
It's a page that has a bulleted list of the main 
points that are in the ATAG standard. So that is

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:58.880
something you could review at your own pace. But 
today we'll also go through a bunch of different

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:06.720
guidelines that are in ATAG - success criteria 
- and I hope to give you a good overview of what

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:12.800
you can find in ATAG and how it can really help 
end users and people who edit content on the web.

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:19.360
Now, the ATAG standard consists of two parts. 
The first part is about the editing experience,

00:09:19.360 --> 00:09:26.000
so the content editing itself, the, the backends 
for example, and the second part is about the

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:32.080
output of content. I'll focus mostly on 
output today, but also talk a bit about

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:35.840
what we can do to improve the editing 
experience for people with disabilities.

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:42.240
Yeah, let's look at that first. So, part 
A of ATAG is about the accessibility of

00:09:42.240 --> 00:09:47.680
the editing experience. So the very 
first success criteria, on A.1.1.1,

00:09:47.680 --> 00:09:53.760
is about making sure that your interface conforms 
to the WCAG standard. And part of that, of course,

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:58.320
is making sure that your interface works with text 
zoom. It's something I heard a lot from users,

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:03.920
uh, when I talk to them for my work. It's 
when they zoom in the interface they are,

00:10:03.920 --> 00:10:08.480
it's not as easy for them to use the interface, 
or sometimes the interface becomes completely

00:10:08.480 --> 00:10:13.520
unusable. So testing with text zoom is one thing 
you can do. Text alternatives for icons. It's

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:19.040
very common these days to have interfaces that 
consist of just icons. So, if you work on the,

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:23.680
on a plugin, or a theme, or something that has 
an editing interface where icons are the main

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:28.080
thing you click on, make sure that there are 
text alternatives for them, so that there's an

00:10:28.080 --> 00:10:34.640
accessible name somewhere in the source code. Make 
it work with a keyboard is another great advice.

00:10:35.280 --> 00:10:39.600
And that includes things like visible focus, so 
that you can see, at all times, where you are on

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:44.240
the page, before you interact with something, and 
that you can use all controls. So that includes

00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:51.120
all form fields, anchors, and buttons. Another 
recommendation in ATAG is about displaying

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:55.840
previews accessibly. Because most content 
management systems, or authoring tools in general,

00:10:56.400 --> 00:11:00.480
plugins as well, will have some way to 
preview the content that you're working on.

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:07.520
And this material is about making sure that 
that content is accessible, as well. Or you

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:12.080
can think of things like helping with spelling. 
Some people may have dyslexia - they're editing

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:16.400
some content - you can help them a great 
deal by helping them correct their spelling.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.680
Now, that's a bit about the first part of 
ATAG, improving the editing experience.

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:26.880
But what I really promised to talk about today is 
how your CMS could be an accessibility assistant,

00:11:27.680 --> 00:11:32.240
and, in that sense, support the production 
of accessible content, as the official

00:11:32.240 --> 00:11:39.360
name is for part b of ATAG. And for that, let's 
talk a bit about what accessible content is.

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:43.040
It is things like that you have tables 
with headers. That you have forms with the

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:48.560
appropriate labels. That you have hero images with 
plenty of contrast. That videos are captioned.

00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:52.000
That you can have multilingual content 
with the right language attributes.

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:57.120
That everything is nested according to 
specification. That carousels can pause,

00:11:57.120 --> 00:12:01.520
and that you have sensible heading structure. 
So all of these things, they contribute to,

00:12:01.520 --> 00:12:06.640
to more accessible content. So for your end 
users, for the people using the website or,

00:12:06.640 --> 00:12:11.600
you know, web content that you're creating, 
all these things need to be in order. So if

00:12:11.600 --> 00:12:16.640
we want to have a good accessibility assistant, it 
should assist with all of these different things.

00:12:16.640 --> 00:12:21.920
And usually they could be different, different 
products, right? Because sometimes you might have

00:12:21.920 --> 00:12:28.720
a plug-in specifically for creating tables, or one 
specifically for creating forms, so they could be

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:34.800
specialized products that focus on these specific 
tasks. And an accessibility assistant would,

00:12:34.800 --> 00:12:40.000
of course, help avoid inaccessible content. So it 
would avoid things like tables with no headers,

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.160
it would avoid things like form fields 
that have no names, illegible text,

00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:48.720
caption-less videos, multilingual content 
that doesn't have the right lang attributes,

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:55.440
non-standard nesting, carousels that don't have a 
pause button, and headings for the wrong reasons.

00:12:55.440 --> 00:13:00.720
So, a CMS that really helps you get 
your accessibility right will, maybe,

00:13:00.720 --> 00:13:05.840
warn you for these kinds of mistakes, or it will 
generate markup that doesn't have these problems,

00:13:06.560 --> 00:13:10.800
and, and provide templates that 
comes with with the right stuff.

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:15.840
So that's what this is all about. We 
want to avoid inaccessible content

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:21.520
for our end users ultimately, and we want to 
help the people that are using our products,

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:27.040
like our CMS, or our plugin, or our theme. We 
want to help them avoid inaccessible content,

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:34.240
so that they can ship a website that is 
accessible and find problems before they ship it,

00:13:34.240 --> 00:13:39.360
ideally. So a great CMS can really help content 
managers make their content more accessible.

00:13:40.560 --> 00:13:48.080
Think about things like when content is created, 
it is accessible, which is the success criterion

00:13:48.080 --> 00:13:52.640
1.1.2 - B.1.1.2 in, in the ATAG standard, 
and that is about things like, you know,

00:13:52.640 --> 00:13:56.880
you need to make sure that it's nested according 
to the standard, you want to make sure there's no

00:13:56.880 --> 00:14:03.120
empty links inside of this content. Sometimes, 
to make content accessible, you need some more

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:08.160
information. So maybe you need to prompt the 
user for required accessibility information, like

00:14:08.160 --> 00:14:15.200
a caption for table, an alternative text for an 
image, or for video, those sorts of things. You,

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:19.600
you need to prompt for, if you know that, that 
could cause an accessibility problem. and,

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:24.000
you know, you rely on the content editor to 
provide the information, you'll need to prompt

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:29.440
for it. So, uh, captions for tables, alt text for 
images, and labels for form fields, are just some

00:14:29.440 --> 00:14:34.800
examples of things that you could prompt for. Or 
when content is generated, maybe there could be

00:14:34.800 --> 00:14:40.880
automated accessibility checks. Or if it can only 
be checked manually, maybe the tools could suggest

00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:47.280
to the user to do a manual check. For instance, 
if it's about the heading structure of the page,

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:53.280
or if it is about text alternatives, maybe 
they are centrally managed, and you want the

00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:58.560
user to make sure that the text alternative makes 
sense for this specific use case. For instance a

00:14:58.560 --> 00:15:04.160
photo of a speaker, but their name is also in the 
content, so maybe at that point you would want a

00:15:04.160 --> 00:15:10.720
zero, or you would want an empty alternative text, 
rather than repeat the name of the speaker, so

00:15:10.720 --> 00:15:15.840
that sort of thing, that requires a manual check. 
Someone who knows the content and understands it

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:20.800
to, to go through it, and as an authoring 
tool, as a CMS you could actually provide

00:15:20.800 --> 00:15:26.640
the right instructions and help the the user to 
figure out how to make their content accessible.

00:15:28.720 --> 00:15:34.640
2.1.1 is about allowing to create accessible 
content. So, not everyone realizes this, but there

00:15:34.640 --> 00:15:40.960
are a lot of authoring tools out there that don't 
provide, or don't allow for entering accessible

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:47.200
content. For instance, if you upload a video, if 
there's no caption it isn't accessible - but if

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:54.240
your video widget doesn't have a caption button, 
then you know the user cannot create an accessible

00:15:54.240 --> 00:15:59.520
video with your authoring tool. Or if there's no 
alternative text option. And some social media.

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:03.680
for instance. only recently added the option 
to add alternative text. And there is a bunch

00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:08.960
of social media out there that still don't have 
that option available. So even if users want to

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:13.120
create accessible content, they are not able to, 
because there's no option for alternative text.

00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:17.360
So, for image fields, that means there 
should be an alternative text field,

00:16:17.360 --> 00:16:23.280
and for video players there should be an upload 
button for captions. And this is specifically

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:28.560
important for those creating plugins that deal 
with video or, or images. Make sure that people

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:33.520
can manage their alternative text, so that they 
can create accessible content in the first place.

00:16:35.600 --> 00:16:40.080
Something else that ATAG recommends is to have 
accessible templates for the most common use

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:46.800
cases, and to be able to filter for that. Um, 
I know there is a filter available in the,

00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:51.520
in the WordPress directory of different 
themes, so that is another important way

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:57.280
that you can help content editors make the 
right decisions. And there's a B.2.5.1,

00:16:57.280 --> 00:17:02.400
which says that you should provide accessible UI 
components. Or, as the specification calls it,

00:17:02.400 --> 00:17:08.080
"pre-authored content." So when you provide 
something like a carousel, or, or tabs component,

00:17:08.720 --> 00:17:14.240
and users can add that into the page, make sure 
that they are accessible by default, so that the

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:20.640
content editor doesn't need to do anything - it 
just ships as an accessible component. So it makes

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:26.320
a lot of sense to spend time on accessibility 
if you provide something like a carousel tool,

00:17:27.040 --> 00:17:32.240
because everyone is going to use your plugin 
is going to have a more accessible website. So,

00:17:32.240 --> 00:17:38.320
it's going to have a huge, a huge effect if 
you spend that extra time on on accessibility,

00:17:38.320 --> 00:17:44.560
for all of those end users, specifically. 
So here's some interpretation of B.3.1.1

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:51.200
which is, why don't warn users when they introduce 
a color contrast issue? Say you work at an agency,

00:17:51.200 --> 00:17:56.640
and a designer has produced this beautiful header 
with a dark photo of a black cat with white text

00:17:56.640 --> 00:18:01.680
on top of it. It has perfect contrast, and it's 
been checked according to the accessibility

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:07.520
guidelines. This is good, it passes all the tests, 
but then someone decides to replace the photo

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:14.400
with one of Korean food, in this case. And it is 
a perfectly valid photo - but it is very light,

00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:18.800
and the text is also light, so at this point, 
when we drop in this photo, we've introduced

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:24.240
a color contrast issue. And it's possible to 
programmatically detect color contrast problems.

00:18:24.880 --> 00:18:29.600
And with that, you could provide a warning for the 
content author that something is going wrong here.

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:34.000
You could say, well, there's not enough contrast 
- maybe there should be background color

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:39.680
painted behind this text to fix the problem, or in 
some cases a larger text, or a bolder font could

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:45.440
be just enough to address the problem. Something 
else that you could do is to add a spell checker

00:18:45.440 --> 00:18:53.840
to content fields. I have a button here that says 
"Swpmit," which, I guess for visual sighted users,

00:18:53.840 --> 00:18:58.240
they might parse it in their head and see that it 
probably says "submit," because the "w" looks so

00:18:58.240 --> 00:19:03.440
much like a "u," but if you are trying to 
use some assistive technology, it's going

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:08.880
to be pretty tricky to use this button, and it's 
going to read it out weirdly in a screen reader.

00:19:08.880 --> 00:19:14.320
If you use something like Naturally Speaking, it's 
going to be hard to identify the specific button.

00:19:14.320 --> 00:19:18.240
So if there was a spell checker, you could 
avoid these accessibility problems altogether.

00:19:19.840 --> 00:19:24.320
Something else that you could automatically do 
is report readability levels. And I think I've

00:19:24.320 --> 00:19:30.080
seen this in some SEO plugins, but it's also very 
valid thing to do for accessibility, to make sure

00:19:30.080 --> 00:19:35.360
that the text is nice and easy to read. And you 
could have readability levels, uh, warn the user

00:19:35.360 --> 00:19:39.840
when they've added text that's too complicated and 
maybe help them fix the problems there, as well.

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:47.040
Something else that the standard recommends is 
to provide accessible examples. So if you work

00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:53.760
on documentation, you can do a great deal, as 
well, about accessibility of your CMS or plugin

00:19:53.760 --> 00:19:59.280
by making sure that all of the examples really 
help the user to get their accessibility right.

00:19:59.280 --> 00:20:02.320
Sometimes that means the stuff 
that maybe gets copy/pasted,

00:20:02.320 --> 00:20:07.120
really ensuring that everything there 
is perfectly accessible. Sometimes,

00:20:07.120 --> 00:20:11.600
it means providing the right guidelines. 
Like, you know, if you leave this field empty,

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:16.080
there won't be alternative text, so make sure you 
put something in there. Or explain, kind of, how

00:20:16.080 --> 00:20:22.080
alternative text works. So it's really putting in 
an extra mile and making sure that the example is,

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:29.760
is accessible and really encourages good 
accessibility. So, basically, a good CMS can

00:20:29.760 --> 00:20:34.720
encourage more accessible content and help 
people get their accessibility right. Now,

00:20:34.720 --> 00:20:39.600
I've talked about the standard quite a bit, but I 
think one of the exciting things about authoring

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:45.840
tools that help with accessibility is that it can 
really help with your process. Let's look now at

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:52.960
when, in the process, authoring tools can help. 
Now process is a bit of a tricky subject, I think,

00:20:52.960 --> 00:20:57.520
because whoever you talk to, depending on their 
organization, they will have different ways of

00:20:57.520 --> 00:21:02.240
organizing their projects. Now this is an example 
of a process that your organization might be

00:21:02.240 --> 00:21:08.640
following, if it follows the waterfall principles. 
So you might start with some planning and strategy

00:21:08.640 --> 00:21:13.760
sessions, and do interaction design and visual 
design, then development and QA, then launch.

00:21:14.960 --> 00:21:20.160
You might have a process that is much more 
multidisciplinary, so you might have all the

00:21:20.160 --> 00:21:25.760
disciplines working together in iterations, 
and that could be a thing in sprints or doing

00:21:25.760 --> 00:21:32.080
something like scrum. Um, or you might be going 
back and forth between these phases. Like going

00:21:32.080 --> 00:21:37.360
back from launch, to strategy, or to interaction 
design, or sometimes maybe from QA to design.

00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:43.440
Whatever you're doing, I think there is 
a lot to say about where authoring tools

00:21:43.440 --> 00:21:48.000
fit into the process. For instance, if 
you're working in planning and strategy,

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:52.240
you can make a huge difference by choosing an 
authoring tool that supports accessibility in

00:21:52.240 --> 00:21:59.360
the ways that I outlined before. So adopting a lot 
of the principles in ATAG, and really helping the,

00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:05.040
the user to get their accessibility right, can 
really help in the long run, because if that's

00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:10.160
the case, then later on in the process, it'll 
be much easier for the organization to create

00:22:10.160 --> 00:22:16.400
webpages that are accessible. In the interaction 
design phase, you could spend a great deal on how

00:22:17.440 --> 00:22:22.400
content should be authored in an accessible 
manner. You could test the authoring process

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:27.280
with people with disabilities, if user testing is 
part of your your interaction design discipline.

00:22:28.240 --> 00:22:34.240
If you're doing visual design, you could provide 
guidelines for customizing color, so that contrast

00:22:34.240 --> 00:22:41.040
works well. You could work on accessible examples, 
like large enough touch targets. Uh, all these

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:46.080
sorts of things, uh, can help you in a design 
phase, to make sure that anyone who's authoring,

00:22:46.080 --> 00:22:50.800
uh, web pages later on, because you might not 
be designing every single web page - it might

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:56.720
happen in the templating phase, and then content 
people might work with designs that were created.

00:22:56.720 --> 00:23:00.160
So providing some guidelines there can 
really help in the authoring phase.

00:23:01.120 --> 00:23:06.000
When we're talking about development, you could 
make a great difference by picking a theme that

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:12.080
has accessibility support, or plug-in with 
accessibility support. Because, again, you'll

00:23:12.080 --> 00:23:18.160
help people who create web content to do that in 
a more accessible manner, or sometimes get a lot

00:23:18.160 --> 00:23:23.040
of accessibility for free, if there's a carousel 
component or something that was built accessibly.

00:23:24.160 --> 00:23:29.120
When it comes to QA, you could embed automated 
accessibility tests in the authoring process.

00:23:29.680 --> 00:23:34.080
So, for instance, if someone 
creates a new page and presses save

00:23:34.080 --> 00:23:37.280
that there are some tests that are 
running automatically. If you have some

00:23:37.840 --> 00:23:43.040
test automation engineers in your team, take 
advantage of them, and let them help make the

00:23:43.040 --> 00:23:49.280
authoring process more valuable as well in terms 
of accessibility. And then, when you launch, you

00:23:49.280 --> 00:23:54.240
may have something that is much more accessible 
than if you wouldn't have done all those, those

00:23:54.240 --> 00:24:00.400
things, uh, because many websites are launched 
without much required for accessibility, sadly.

00:24:01.200 --> 00:24:06.720
That still happens. And those websites might find 
that they then hire accessibility consultants,

00:24:06.720 --> 00:24:12.720
get a big list of issues that they never thought 
of, and it might take them a lot more time to,

00:24:12.720 --> 00:24:17.680
to work through all of those issues. So if you 
start very much in the planning phase, and think

00:24:17.680 --> 00:24:21.840
about accessibility in all of these different 
phases - and I know that's not a new thing,

00:24:22.480 --> 00:24:27.200
but I just want to say that that really makes 
a big difference. And if you think of authoring

00:24:27.200 --> 00:24:32.960
in all of these phases, that can really help 
create much more accessible things by default.

00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:41.440
Now it may be clear to you by now, that at WAI 
we find authoring tools are really important part

00:24:41.440 --> 00:24:47.040
of web accessibility. And to that extent we're, 
you know, we're doing a number of things to, uh,

00:24:47.040 --> 00:24:54.480
to improve the situation. The first thing is, um, 
I just wanted to mention that if the ATAG standard

00:24:54.480 --> 00:25:01.280
itself is a bit of a long read. There is also the 
Implementing ATAG 2.0 document that has rationale

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:05.920
and intent for each of the success criteria, and 
a bunch of different practical examples. And I've

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:11.600
taken some of the examples in this presentation 
from there, as well. It helps to understand ATAG

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:18.480
a bit better, if you you get stuck in in the main 
ATAG document. Now, something that I'm involved

00:25:18.480 --> 00:25:23.120
with personally is something called the WAI 
Guide project. And one thing that we're creating

00:25:23.120 --> 00:25:29.520
as part of that, to help people use the authoring 
process that I just outlined right, really putting

00:25:29.520 --> 00:25:36.000
authoring tools at the front and center, to help 
you get your accessibility right. We want to help

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:40.800
people find tools that support accessibility. So 
we've created a list of authoring tools where you

00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:47.440
can filter by ATAG criteria and find tools that 
support accessibility. Now this is all still dummy

00:25:47.440 --> 00:25:54.240
data that you can see here - it's not live yet. 
But we are working on getting our first entries

00:25:54.240 --> 00:25:59.760
into the list, and you know, if you create a 
tool, uh, that you think qualifies for this,

00:25:59.760 --> 00:26:04.640
and has accessibility support, and that meets one 
or more of the ATAG criteria, do get in touch.

00:26:04.640 --> 00:26:10.000
I'd be interested to, to hear from you. Um, at 
the same time, we're also working on something

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:18.320
called the ATAG Report Tool, where you can report 
on ATAG criteria. So you can fill in some details,

00:26:18.320 --> 00:26:22.320
and then you go to each of the guidelines, 
and then you will say whether it passes or

00:26:22.320 --> 00:26:27.840
fails. And you can fill in some information 
about each of them. Now this is kind of on an

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:34.000
optional basis, so each of these are optional. You 
can fill in the ones that you want to showcase,

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:38.880
so if you particularly deal with one of 
the criteria well, then you fill in those,

00:26:38.880 --> 00:26:43.360
and maybe leave the others empty. Of course 
we want to have as many criteria as possible,

00:26:43.360 --> 00:26:49.280
that will also make it easier for people to 
find your tool in our list, but yeah, we welcome

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:56.800
reports this way as well. In this tool, you 
are able to create a report in JSON or HTML

00:26:57.920 --> 00:27:02.720
and you can also publish that on your website to 
showcase how well you meet ATAG. And, ultimately,

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:06.400
you would be able to create a listing in the 
authoring tools list that we're working on.

00:27:06.960 --> 00:27:11.520
At the moment there's not that connection yet, 
because it's still in its early phases, bu,t

00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:16.320
yeah. Very much interested to hearing 
your feedback on this tool, as well.

00:27:17.200 --> 00:27:24.320
Now, going to conclusions, uh, what I wanted to 
share with you today is very much that CMSs are

00:27:24.320 --> 00:27:31.040
essential for an accessible web. It won't surprise 
you, as people who work on, on CMS's and plugins,

00:27:31.040 --> 00:27:37.200
and maybe themes, even, but yeah, your work is 
very important for website, web accessibility.

00:27:37.200 --> 00:27:42.800
I hope this, this talk gave some more insights in 
more ways that it, that it does. Now, secondly,

00:27:42.800 --> 00:27:47.840
I think CMSs should really help content editors 
get their accessibility right. And I open this

00:27:47.840 --> 00:27:53.120
talk about, like, the number of ways in which 
they, they can, so yeah. Hopefully, we can really

00:27:53.120 --> 00:27:59.040
see our CMSs as accessibility assistants, um, and 
that's the question I want to leave you with: How

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:05.120
would you turn your CMS, your plugin, your theme 
into a better assistant for web accessibility?

00:28:05.120 --> 00:28:08.240
For now, thanks very much for 
listening. You can find the slides on

00:28:08.240 --> 00:28:13.840
talks.hiddedevries.nl. It is also, it's 
also going to have all the resources, links,

00:28:15.120 --> 00:28:20.720
and video, ultimately, I think. Uh, if you have 
any questions, feel free to get in touch. It's

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:27.760
hidde@w3.org, or you can reach out on Twitter. 
Now I'm going to be showing off in a live Q and A

00:28:27.760 --> 00:28:33.040
right after this, so then I want to just thank you 
for listening, and shout out to the organizers of

00:28:33.040 --> 00:28:43.840
WordPress Accessibility Day. Thanks so much for 
putting this event on, and inviting me to speak.

00:28:47.720 --> 00:28:55.360
[Ahmed] Thank you so much, Hidde, with that 
presentation. We actually was able to learn

00:28:55.360 --> 00:29:03.120
a lot of things that are very, very important to 
choosing CMSs, and we have a bunch of questions.

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:07.520
So, let's just start with the first 
one, while a few more comes in. So,

00:29:07.520 --> 00:29:14.320
the first question we have for you is, "What would 
be the most important feature you must change in

00:29:14.320 --> 00:29:19.440
Gutenberg to be completely accessible? If you need 
to correct something, you could also do that."

00:29:20.680 --> 00:29:27.760
[Hidde] Yeah, so I'm probably not the right person 
to ask, because I don't work on, on Gutenberg. I

00:29:27.760 --> 00:29:32.880
think one very interesting presentation that would 
get you up to date with the latest on Gutenberg

00:29:32.880 --> 00:29:39.280
Accessibility is by Joe Dolson at the WordPress 
Campus. The video of that has recently been

00:29:39.280 --> 00:29:44.880
released, and I think that will give you a good 
overview of the stuff that that team is working

00:29:44.880 --> 00:29:50.320
on, sometimes struggling with, uh, sometimes 
really massively improving. So there's, there's a

00:29:50.320 --> 00:29:56.880
lot of work happening on uh, on Gutenberg, which I 
think is great. It's hard to make a, an editor of

00:29:56.880 --> 00:30:02.960
the future, and also do it accessibly, so I admire 
the effort. I think it's, uh, there's lots of

00:30:02.960 --> 00:30:08.480
great work happening there, but I don't have 
too much to say about the actual issues there.

00:30:09.560 --> 00:30:18.400
[Ahmed] Awesome. Next one is your suggestion 
if you know of any good tool for developers

00:30:18.400 --> 00:30:26.240
to test the different levels of accessibility - A, 
AA, or triple A. [Hidde] Yeah, so, those levels,

00:30:26.240 --> 00:30:31.200
they actually exist in multiple standards. So 
most people will refer to them when they look

00:30:31.200 --> 00:30:36.560
at the WCAG standard, that has these, these 
three levels: A, double A, triple A. The ATAG

00:30:36.560 --> 00:30:42.160
standard does as well. Now, for the UAAG standard, 
there's a bunch of different automated test tools

00:30:42.160 --> 00:30:50.160
that try to interpret the rules that are in WCAG 
as test rules and, and run automatically. Um,

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:55.280
for, for ATAG those don't really, uh, don't 
really exist. Uh, so at the W3C we have this

00:30:55.280 --> 00:31:01.680
project called ACT rules, where we try to bring 
different tool vendors together, and work on, uh,

00:31:01.680 --> 00:31:06.640
test rules, harmonize those test rules, so that 
every tool kind of interprets WCAG the same way.

00:31:07.280 --> 00:31:11.520
Uh, I think that's an interesting project to watch 
if you wanna, wanna know more about different

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:18.000
rules that exist. Um, but yeah, you can definitely 
test automatically for WCAG - that is good for

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:23.440
if you're developing a CMS, because one of the 
ATAG guidelines is conform to WCAG, so that's,

00:31:24.160 --> 00:31:28.320
that's good for the editing experience, but it's 
also good for, uh, for the output. So if you check

00:31:28.960 --> 00:31:34.400
the the page that is being generated, or that the 
editor is working on, if you run that through some

00:31:34.400 --> 00:31:41.040
automated test tool, you might also be able to 
prevent some accessibility issues. [Ahmed] Great.

00:31:41.600 --> 00:31:49.760
So, the next question is one of my favorite, 
and this one asks why are we all focusing on

00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:58.680
WCAG and not also on ATAG - is there, uh, bias? 
Is there a priority when we're choosing? [Hidde]

00:31:59.680 --> 00:32:06.400
It's, it's a great question, um, and something we 
noticed at WAI, as well, and, and kind of partly

00:32:06.400 --> 00:32:11.600
the reason why I'm now assigned to, to work on 
this. Uh, we would love more people to embrace

00:32:11.600 --> 00:32:18.720
ATAG and show the benefit of embracing ATAG, not 
just for people who make CMSs, or sell plugins,

00:32:18.720 --> 00:32:24.320
but also for the companies that buy them. 
We feel like there's a unique selling point

00:32:24.320 --> 00:32:28.880
to be made because so many organizations 
are now required by law to be accessible.

00:32:29.520 --> 00:32:33.920
And if your tool can help them, you might be 
able to charge them more money. So we feel like

00:32:33.920 --> 00:32:39.200
there's a lot of benefit to, um, to looking 
at ATAG. It's not happening, or it wasn't

00:32:39.200 --> 00:32:44.240
happening so much, we see more uptake in the 
last year, and more people talking about it.

00:32:45.600 --> 00:32:49.360
We heard, um, Susanna talk earlier about 
the accessibility of authoring tools,

00:32:49.360 --> 00:32:54.320
and we have this, this conference day today, 
so there's more, uh, more talk about it,

00:32:55.200 --> 00:32:59.440
and that is great. We see more people focus on 
it. But I think one of the main reasons is that

00:32:59.440 --> 00:33:04.800
WCAG is a standard that is embraced by so many 
governments worldwide, and the one thing that

00:33:05.440 --> 00:33:11.920
they, uh, put in, into legislation often. ATAG is, 
is not, but it can really help to, to meet that

00:33:11.920 --> 00:33:17.280
WCAG legislation. So I hope to have showed that 
a bit in this talk, as well, that these things

00:33:17.280 --> 00:33:23.760
can really play together. [Ahmed] Awesome. 
Since we talked about the content management

00:33:23.760 --> 00:33:28.560
system being an accessibility assistant, 
the next few questions focuses on WordPress.

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:35.280
So, this is my personal question to you: how 
ready do you think WordPress is, right now,

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:41.600
to serve as an accessibility assistant among 
the CMSs that are out ther? [Hidde] Yeah,

00:33:41.600 --> 00:33:48.000
so I look at a lot of different CMSs for, for my 
work, and my work is vendor-neutral, so to say, so

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:52.080
I don't look too much at specifics. I do 
know in WordPress there are things like,

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:57.120
um, good options for alternative 
text for, for images, so there's,

00:33:57.120 --> 00:34:03.280
uh, clear information on what you should do there, 
I think that's very helpful. Um, there is also

00:34:03.280 --> 00:34:07.680
something about color contrast, I remember? 
That will, um, show you if you have the, the

00:34:07.680 --> 00:34:13.440
wrong color contrast, and help you get it right. 
Uh, I think those are, those are great features.

00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:17.760
Um, I think there's a page structure thing, as 
well, so there's, there's a bunch of things in

00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:23.840
WordPress that really can help people get their 
accessibility right. But also work to do. I think,

00:34:23.840 --> 00:34:27.840
uh, people of the accessibility team, and 
organizer of this, this event, will be more

00:34:27.840 --> 00:34:34.000
up to date with, with the things that are still 
being worked on. [Ahmed] Yeah, we can certainly

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:40.320
look towards the future. So, if you had to 
rate WordPress as an accessibility assistant,

00:34:40.320 --> 00:34:45.760
how would you rate it amongst a double A and 
triple A - I know it can get controversial, but up

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:51.040
to you, if you want to make any comments. [Hidde] 
I, I cannot possibly comment on that, because we

00:34:51.040 --> 00:34:56.800
we look at all the different CMSs, and we want 
everyone to, to meet as many criteria as possible.

00:34:56.800 --> 00:35:02.720
Good thing to mention there is that, um, it's not 
about meeting all of ATAG, or being completely

00:35:02.720 --> 00:35:07.520
compliant. Just like with WCAG, that is pretty 
hard to do, and not many organizations do it.

00:35:08.240 --> 00:35:13.200
Um, and they have to, by law, but you know 
it's a continuous process. And one person

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:19.040
updates one image, it could be inaccessible. The 
point is really to meet as many of these criteria

00:35:19.040 --> 00:35:24.000
as possible, and, um, you know every, every little 
bit really, really helps. And we see that a lot,

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:29.360
that organizations are, are doing that. And 
also that CMSs are making small improvements,

00:35:29.360 --> 00:35:34.720
and they are all helpful, and the end users 
will, will be happy with these huge improvements,

00:35:34.720 --> 00:35:40.640
I think. [Ahmed] Uh, I must admit, Hidde, that 
our talk is certainly sparking a little bit of

00:35:40.640 --> 00:35:46.000
conversation in the chat feed, we're getting a 
few more questions as we speak. We have time,

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:52.320
so the next question is on Craft CMS. 
Is Craft CMS much better than WordPress

00:35:52.320 --> 00:35:59.120
in terms of the accessibility of the editor, 
thoughts? [Hidde] Are you referring to the

00:35:59.120 --> 00:36:06.080
W3C choice of, uh, of CMS? [Ahmed] I suppose 
so, I suppose that's the question. [Hidde] Uh,

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:10.960
so I'd really like to refer to the the blog post 
I've already published about this, because, um, I

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:17.920
had a tiny part in, in discussing this internally, 
of course. Um, the main, the main points are we,

00:36:18.480 --> 00:36:24.240
we found not many, um, not many tools meet all 
of our criteria that we need, and that's a lot

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:28.960
of different criteria. So we, we need an 
accessible CMS, we need a CMS that supports

00:36:28.960 --> 00:36:31.600
internationalization, because we 
work with the global community,

00:36:32.160 --> 00:36:37.600
um, bunch of different things, basically, 
that we've decided our CMS choice based on.

00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:43.840
Accessibility was, was one of them, and in my work 
I really tried to convince other organizations to

00:36:43.840 --> 00:36:49.040
do what we did - make accessibility part of that 
choice, because, uh, it's going to help you in the

00:36:49.040 --> 00:36:55.680
process, like I showed in the slides. Um, they did 
that, so the, the vendor that we hired for the,

00:36:55.680 --> 00:37:02.080
the new website they, they looked at these 
different, um, aspects and also at accessibility,

00:37:02.080 --> 00:37:08.400
uh, and they looked at how they, how they feel 
it is going to improve. And that is, you know,

00:37:08.400 --> 00:37:12.960
that's a different, difficult thing to, uh, 
to assess. Because, you know, you cannot look

00:37:12.960 --> 00:37:19.120
into the future. Um, but yeah, it seems like, 
like for them that the, the Craft CMS had, had

00:37:19.120 --> 00:37:25.520
more commitment, uh maybe also from the top, to, 
uh, to make their accessibility features better.

00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:31.280
Um, but yeah, maybe WordPress will be a better 
choice for other organizations. It's really tricky

00:37:31.280 --> 00:37:37.920
to, uh, to say, and I can't comment in too much 
detail about that. [Ahmed] That's fair enough. Uh,

00:37:37.920 --> 00:37:43.760
then, I, I think I can understand where 
you're coming from. So, uh, such forum, when,

00:37:43.760 --> 00:37:51.040
where we discuss and we try to assess, uh, CMSs, 
if they're accessibility-ready, so such questions

00:37:51.040 --> 00:37:57.520
are quite realistic, I suppose. But then again, I 
request you to go through our website and answer

00:37:57.520 --> 00:38:03.280
the question. I'm sure you will be given the link 
later, also viewers, we've also shared the slides

00:38:03.280 --> 00:38:09.040
to the presentation by Hidde. Before, I can ask 
you the last question. So, the last one says:

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:17.840
Have you tried to use ACF and a headless front-end 
as editor to get accessibility content creation?

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:26.480
[Hidde] Yes. Not in my capacity at the W3C, but 
I do have from personal experience with that.

00:38:28.240 --> 00:38:34.640
Something in general you can say about, um, 
so, so ACF is an Advanced Custom Field, right,

00:38:34.640 --> 00:38:40.800
